{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"bd65d893-b1aa-46e2-a4ae-d84c04338571","content":"You're on **MSTest 3.8.2 / .NET 9**, so you can use the modern patterns:\n\n- **`TestContext`** — inject via **constructor** (MSTest v3+)\n- **Sync init** — use `[TestInitialize]`\n- **Async init** — use `[TestInitialize]` with `async Task`\n\nHere's the recommended pattern:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests\n{\n    private readonly TestContext _testContext;\n\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        // Constructor: inject TestContext, set readonly fields\n        _testContext = testContext;\n    }\n\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task SetupAsync()\n    {\n        // Synchronous work\n        // ...\n\n        // Asynchronous work\n        await SomeServiceAsync();\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void ExampleTest()\n    {\n        _testContext.WriteLine(\"Running test\");\n        Assert.IsTrue(true);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- Constructor injection of `TestContext` replaces the older `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property pattern.\n- `[TestInitialize]` can return `void` (sync) or `Task` (async) — combine both kinds of work in one method.\n- Use `[ClassInitialize]` / `[ClassCleanup]` (static) for one-time expensive setup shared across all tests in the class.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3031b583-2c3a-4007-bb69-acc300a9056d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"They're using MSTest 3.8.2 on .NET 9.0. In modern MSTest (v3+), the recommended patterns are:\n\n1. **TestContext injection**: Use a constructor parameter or the `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property. In MSTest v3+, constructor injection is supported.\n\n2. **Synchronous initialization**: Use `[TestInitialize]` method.\n\n3. **Asynchronous initialization**: Use `[TestInitialize]` with an `async Task` return type (supported in MSTest v2+).\n\nActually, let me think about this more carefully for MSTest 3.x:\n\n\n- `TestContext` can be injected via constructor in MSTest 3.x\n- `[TestInitialize]` supports both sync and async\n- You can also use `[ClassInitialize]` for class-level setup\n\nThe key modern MSTest patterns are constructor injection for `TestContext` and `[TestInitialize]` for per-test setup, whether sync or async.","outputTokens":623,"requestId":"4C1E:1EBC53:8054F4:A009BA:6A01319F"},"id":"63fb19fa-9964-4c05-9818-efb9cb44002c","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:32:29.240Z","parentId":"c607a4e1-a7db-41ec-9381-45eca357ba22"}
